// ============================================================================
// Verilator lint flags for {{ip_name}} (BSV-generated Verilog)
//
// Usage: verilator --lint-only $(cat verilator.flags) ...
//
// BSV (Bluespec) generates Verilog with idioms that trigger certain Verilator
// warnings which are safe to suppress. This file tunes the warnings for a
// clean, actionable lint report.
//
// Author: {{author}} <{{email}}>
// ============================================================================

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Enable all warnings as the baseline, then selectively suppress.
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
-Wall

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Warnings suppressed for BSV-generated code
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

// UNUSED: BSV generates signals/ports that may be unconnected at the top level
// (e.g. RDY_* signals that are not consumed). Safe to suppress globally.
-Wno-UNUSED

// UNDRIVEN: BSV can leave module ports undriven when interfaces are only
// partially used. These are benign in generated code.
-Wno-UNDRIVEN

// PINCONNECTEMPTY: BSV wrappers often leave submodule output ports
// unconnected. Verilator flags these; they are expected.
-Wno-PINCONNECTEMPTY

// DECLFILENAME: BSV generates module names (mk{{ip_name|capitalize}}, etc.) that may not
// match the filename. This is standard BSV output structure.
-Wno-DECLFILENAME

// WIDTH: BSV frequently uses width-mismatched assignments internally
// (e.g. packing/unpacking structs). Most are intentional truncations or
// zero-extensions inserted by the BSV compiler.
-Wno-WIDTH

// CASEINCOMPLETE: BSV rule scheduling can produce case statements that appear
// incomplete to Verilator but are fully covered by BSV's CAN_FIRE guards.
-Wno-CASEINCOMPLETE

// CASEOVERLAP: BSV may generate overlapping case items for priority-encoded
// rule selection. These are correct by construction.
-Wno-CASEOVERLAP

// INITIALDLY / STMTDLY: kept ENABLED. Waveform dumping now lives in the
// testbench (tb/dump.v), so the linted netlist should contain no initial
// blocks with delays — if these fire, sim-only code leaked into the RTL.

// BLKSEQ: BSV generates blocking assignments inside always @(posedge clk)
// blocks for combinational temporaries. The BSV compiler ensures correct
// semantics; these are safe.
-Wno-BLKSEQ

// COMBDLY: BSV may use non-blocking assignments in combinational blocks
// as part of its scheduling model. Safe for generated code.
-Wno-COMBDLY

// SYNCASYNCNET: the project's fixed reset convention (CLAUDE.md) is
// asynchronous, active-low reset project-wide. BSC's own codegen for this
// pattern uses RST_N both as an async reset edge (in always @(posedge CLK or
// negedge RST_N)) and, separately, as a synchronous reset-value check inside
// CSR/register logic (e.g. mkConfigCSR_*_Reg.v) — expected on every BSC IP
// under this convention, not a per-IP issue.
-Wno-SYNCASYNCNET

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Warnings kept ENABLED (these catch real issues even in BSV output)
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

// MULTIDRIVEN — Multiple drivers on a net indicate a real conflict.
// UNSIGNED    — Unsigned comparison issues may reveal logic bugs.
// LITENDIAN   — Little-endian bit ranges can indicate port mismatches.
// IMPORTSTAR  — Wildcard imports can mask naming issues.

// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
// Lint-related options
// ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

// Generate XML output for downstream tooling (optional; remove if not needed)
// --xml-only

// Limit error count before aborting (0 = unlimited)
-error-limit 200
